<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="577" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,817,1168]" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">
<taxonomicName authority="Barraclough, 1993" authorityName="Barraclough" authorityYear="1993" box="[151,271,818,844]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Courtoisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,271,818,844]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Courtoisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected for two very similar species of 
<taxonomicName box="[777,941,817,843]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Taeniapterinae">Taeniapterinae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1851" box="[959,1161,817,843]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Calobata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis box="[959,1161,817,843]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Calobata apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1177,1267,817,843]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1963,1988]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,166,1942]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[201,1386,166,1943]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. A, Courtoisia apicalis (Macquart) holotype. B, Courtoisia trinotata (Macquart) lectotype. Specimens from the Bigot collection, Oxford. Photographs by Zoë Simmons" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3265633/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Calobata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trinotata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Calobata trinotata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[267,354,853,879]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1963,1988]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,166,1942]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[201,1386,166,1943]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. A, Courtoisia apicalis (Macquart) holotype. B, Courtoisia trinotata (Macquart) lectotype. Specimens from the Bigot collection, Oxford. Photographs by Zoë Simmons" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3265633/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
)) endemic to the Mascarene Islands, both described by Macquart from 
<collectingCountry box="[1182,1277,853,879]" name="Réunion" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Réunion</collectingCountry>
and probably closely related to the continental Afrotropical genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Hennig" authorityName="Hennig" authorityYear="1935" box="[765,1017,889,915]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cephalosphen" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[765,925,889,915]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Cephalosphen</emphasis>
Hennig
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Verbeke (Barraclough, 1993)" authorityName="Verbeke (Barraclough" authorityYear="1993" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Erythromyiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1077,1246,889,915]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Erythromyiella</emphasis>
Verbeke (
<bibRefCitation author="Barraclough, D. A." pageId="1" pageNumber="577" pagination="121 - 126" refId="ref2863" refString="Barraclough, D. A. (1993) A new genus of taeniapterine Micropezidae (Diptera) from the Mascarene Islands. Systematic Entomology, 18, 121 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1993. tb 00657. x" type="journal article" year="1993">Barraclough, 1993</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Only one 
<taxonomicName authority="Barraclough, 1993" authorityName="Barraclough" authorityYear="1993" box="[435,555,926,952]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Courtoisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[435,555,926,952]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Courtoisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen, a female recorded at Magenta, 
<collectingCountry box="[1034,1143,925,951]" name="Mauritius" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
in 1963 and identified by Barraclough as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1851" box="[325,446,961,988]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Calobata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis box="[325,344,962,988]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[357,446,961,987]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has been collected since the original description; 
<bibRefCitation author="Barraclough, D. A." box="[1004,1223,961,987]" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" pagination="121 - 126" refId="ref2863" refString="Barraclough, D. A. (1993) A new genus of taeniapterine Micropezidae (Diptera) from the Mascarene Islands. Systematic Entomology, 18, 121 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1993. tb 00657. x" type="journal article" year="1993">Barraclough (1993)</bibRefCitation>
speculated that the genus might be extinct. 
<collectingCountry box="[426,521,997,1023]" name="Réunion" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Réunion</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[578,687,997,1023]" name="Mauritius" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
have been extensively sampled for all groups of 
<taxonomicName box="[1251,1335,997,1023]" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
over the past decade, without turning up any further specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Barraclough, 1993" authorityName="Barraclough" authorityYear="1993" box="[811,931,1034,1060]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Courtoisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[811,931,1034,1060]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Courtoisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Barraclough, 1993" authorityName="Barraclough" authorityYear="1993" box="[947,1067,1034,1060]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Courtoisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[947,1067,1034,1060]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Courtoisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be distinctive for the maculate wing, the duplicated postalar setae (as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hennig" authorityName="Hennig" authorityYear="1935" box="[729,981,1069,1096]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cephalosphen" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[729,889,1069,1095]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="577">Cephalosphen</emphasis>
Hennig
</taxonomicName>
) and the row of short setae on the gena. External features of both species were thoroughly redescribed and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Barraclough, D. A." box="[1081,1304,1105,1131]" pageId="1" pageNumber="577" pagination="121 - 126" refId="ref2863" refString="Barraclough, D. A. (1993) A new genus of taeniapterine Micropezidae (Diptera) from the Mascarene Islands. Systematic Entomology, 18, 121 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1993. tb 00657. x" type="journal article" year="1993">Barraclough (1993)</bibRefCitation>
and, in the absence of new material, there is nothing further to add here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
